		<item>
		<title>Restaurant CAPEX Spend Goes Hand-in-Hand with Revenue Growth</title>
		<link>https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-capex</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Aaron Allen]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 29 Sep 2018 17:39:36 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Insights]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Restaurant Finance]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://aaronallen.com/?p=12317</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Capital is cheaper and more available than ever, and at least in the U.S. corporate profits are at record levels. Many organizations are using this opportunity to make strategic acquisitions or to increase stock prices by buying back shares and paying out larger dividends. But the strong correlation between CAPEX investments and revenue growth argues &#8230; </p>
<p class="link-more"><a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-capex" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> "Restaurant CAPEX Spend Goes Hand-in-Hand with Revenue Growth"</span></a></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-capex">Restaurant CAPEX Spend Goes Hand-in-Hand with Revenue Growth</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://aaronallen.com">Aaron Allen &amp; Associates, Global Restaurant Consultants</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[		<div data-elementor-type="wp-post" data-elementor-id="12317" class="elementor elementor-12317">
						<div class="elementor-inner">
				<div class="elementor-section-wrap">
									<section class="elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-a8f9672 elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default" data-id="a8f9672" data-element_type="section">
						<div class="elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default">
							<div class="elementor-row">
					<div class="elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-e86db07" data-id="e86db07" data-element_type="column">
			<div class="elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated">
							<div class="elementor-widget-wrap">
						<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-ba75030 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="ba75030" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<p>Capital is cheaper and more available than ever, and at least in the U.S. corporate profits are at record levels. Many organizations are using this opportunity to make <a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-mergers-and-acquisitions">strategic acquisitions</a> or to increase stock prices by <a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/stock-buybacks-dividend-distributions">buying back shares</a> and paying out larger dividends. But the strong correlation between CAPEX investments and revenue growth argues for a different strategy: putting capital back into the system.</p>
<ul>
 	<li>Public restaurants in the U.S. that spent 10.4% or more on CAPEX between 2012 and 2017 experienced an average of 11.9% revenue growth, almost twice the 6.0% average CAGR.</li>
 	<li>Despite being able to delegate the costs of new units, remodels, and upgrades to franchisees, highly franchised systems still devote an average 5.9% of their revenue to capital expenditures.</li>
</ul>
For chains with smaller footprints, adding units can help quickly add revenue. For those operations that have reached the saturation point, updating and remodeling locations not only allows for improvements in efficiency and tech integration but also builds excitement among guests and media. Indeed, both in- and outside the restaurant industry, investments in technology are creating incredible ROIs in the form of increased market cap and valuation. But not all CAPEX is created equal: these investments work best when they align with long-term <a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-strategic-planning">strategic planning</a> informed by a comprehensive understanding of the factors and forces shaping the <a href="https://aaronallen.com/restaurant-research">global restaurant industry</a>.
<h2>Top-Quartile Performers Double Spend on CAPEX, Earn 6.6x Revenue Growth</h2>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		</div>
								</div>
					</div>
		</section>
