		<item>
		<title>Restaurant Profit Margin: The Ultimate Guide</title>
		<link>https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-profit-margin</link>
					<comments>https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-profit-margin#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Aaron Allen]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 07 Jul 2018 21:13:59 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Insights]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Restaurant Finance]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://aaronallen.com/?p=10998</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Did you know that the average restaurant has a profit margin of just 7%? That means for every $100 in sales, the restaurant only earns around $7 in profit. As a restaurant CEO or CFO, it&#8217;s important to understand what affects your profit margin and how you can improve it. In this guide, we&#8217;ll explore &#8230; </p>
<p class="link-more"><a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-profit-margin" class="more-link">Continue reading<span class="screen-reader-text"> "Restaurant Profit Margin: The Ultimate Guide"</span></a></p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-profit-margin">Restaurant Profit Margin: The Ultimate Guide</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://aaronallen.com">Aaron Allen &amp; Associates, Global Restaurant Consultants</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[		<div data-elementor-type="wp-post" data-elementor-id="10998" class="elementor elementor-10998">
						<div class="elementor-inner">
				<div class="elementor-section-wrap">
									<section class="elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-28287831 elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default" data-id="28287831" data-element_type="section">
						<div class="elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default">
							<div class="elementor-row">
					<div class="elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-38313bd1" data-id="38313bd1" data-element_type="column">
			<div class="elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated">
							<div class="elementor-widget-wrap">
						<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-b7d3820 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="b7d3820" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<p>Did you know that the average restaurant has a profit margin of just 7%? That means for every $100 in sales, the restaurant only earns around $7 in profit. As a restaurant CEO or CFO, it&#8217;s important to understand what affects your profit margin and how you can improve it. In this guide, we&#8217;ll explore the factors that influence restaurant profit margins and offer tips on how to increase profitability. We&#8217;ll also look at profitability by geography, category, and franchising level. So whether you&#8217;re looking to boost your restaurant&#8217;s bottom line or just want to better understand how it works, read on for insight into restaurant profit margins!</p><h2><strong>How Do You Calculate a Restaurant&#8217;s Profit Margin Percentage?</strong></h2><p>How profitable are the most successful restaurant operations? The answer to that question will change based on the margins used to measure the organization’s performance. Here, we examine four metrics that investors and managers use to gauge a foodservice operation’s profitability: gross margin, operating margin, and profit margin.</p><h3><strong>How to Calculate Gross Margins for Foodservice</strong></h3><p><a href="https://aaronallen.com/blog/restaurant-gross-margin">Gross margin</a> reflects what percentage of revenue a restaurant operation keeps after paying for the costs of the products or services it sells. The higher ratio, the better, indicating a lower cost of goods sold (COGS), which includes any expenditure directly necessary for producing the items on a restaurant’s menu.</p><p>The ratio is calculated using the following expression:</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-21979 size-medium" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Gross-Profit-Margin-300x65.jpg" alt="Gross Profit Margin equals Gross Profit Divided by Total Sales Revenue" width="300" height="65" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Gross-Profit-Margin-300x65.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Gross-Profit-Margin-768x167.jpg 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Gross-Profit-Margin.jpg 936w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p><p>The average restaurant profit measured by the Gross Margin is 45% (considering publicly traded restaurants in the U.S.)</p><h3><strong>How to Calculate a Restaurant Operating Profitability</strong></h3><p><a href="https://corporatefinanceinstitute.com/resources/knowledge/accounting/operating-margin/">Operating profit</a> margin indicates what percentage of revenue remains after all operating costs have been deducted, including COGS, selling, general, and administrative (SG&amp;A) expenses, and others. That is, operating profit includes more costs than gross profit, because it takes into account line items like marketing, managerial salaries, and other expenses not directly related to production.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-21981 size-medium aligncenter" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Operating-Profit-Margin-300x64.jpg" alt="Operating profit margin equals operating profit divided by total sales revenue" width="300" height="64" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Operating-Profit-Margin-300x64.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Operating-Profit-Margin-768x164.jpg 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Operating-Profit-Margin.jpg 936w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p><h3><strong>How to Calculate a Restaurant EBITDA</strong></h3><p>The restaurant industry can be mighty unforgiving because of thin margins and high operating expenses. <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/ebitda.asp">EBITDA (earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization)</a> plays a crucial role, as it is designed to help owners and operators place a firm value on their restaurant company’s earning power by focusing on cash flow.</p><p><strong>EBITDA</strong> is characterized as net cash income, or net operating income. To calculate EBITDA, restaurant owners must subtract their fixed costs from their gross profit. (EBITDA does not reflect noncash expenses such as depreciation and interest payments.) <strong>Operating profit</strong>, on the other hand, is calculated by subtracting the costs of goods sold, plus expenses, from total sales. Many operators and owners view restaurant EBITDA as a useful way of evaluating the actual earnings power of their operation, and to compare their businesses to others carrying different debt levels or depreciation values.</p><p>EBITDA  is a very useful metric to measure corporate profitability and is a good tool for comparing companies, especially within the same industry as it excludes financial effects and capital expenditures.</p><p>It is calculated as follows:</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-21982 size-large" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Ebitda-Definition-1024x67.jpg" alt="EBITDA equals Net Income plus Interest plus Taxes plus Depreciation plus Amortization" width="640" height="42" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Ebitda-Definition-1024x67.jpg 1024w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Ebitda-Definition-300x20.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Ebitda-Definition-768x50.jpg 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Ebitda-Definition.jpg 1100w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></p><p>Careful though! EBITDA essentially neutralizes the cost of debt and adds back income taxes to the net income. Therefore, companies tend to highlight their EBITDA when performance is still very impressive. In fact, a company with a negative net income may have a positive EBITDA.</p><p>The typical restaurant profitability is 12% (EBITDA margin for publicly traded foodservice companies in the U.S.). The top-quartile (the best performers) is passing the 18% profitability margin. And while many of those are highly-franchised companies, most of the best performers are those able to harness headwinds and turn challenges into opportunities. On the other hand, the bottom-quartile (the worst performers) has a profitability (measured by the EBITDA margin) of only 5%.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-21983 size-large" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-1024x679.png" alt="Bar chart EBITDA margin for close to 50 restaurant chains" width="640" height="424" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-1024x679.png 1024w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-300x199.png 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-768x509.png 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-1536x1018.png 1536w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability-1568x1039.png 1568w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/US-Restaurant-Profitability.png 1820w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></p><h3><strong>How to Calculate the Net Profit Margin for a Restaurant </strong></h3><p>The <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/profitmargin.asp">net profit margin</a> ratio includes every expense an organization pays out before calculating the percentage of each revenue dollar it gets to keep. It also considers other sources of revenue besides sales, like interest income.</p><p>While gross and operating margins are entirely under the company’s control, net profit considers line items including taxes, depreciation, debt payments, and extraordinary items.</p><p>Since EBITDA excludes the effect of depreciation and taxes on earnings, it should be complemented by an evaluation of the overall bottom line. By subtracting Depreciation &amp; Amortization, Interest expense and Non-Operating/Unusual expenses (if any), and Taxes, from the EBITDA margin we obtain the Net Income.</p><p>It is calculated as follows:</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-21984 size-medium" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Net-Profit-Margin-Definition-300x72.jpg" alt="Net Profit Margin equals Net Income Divided by Total Revenue" width="300" height="72" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Net-Profit-Margin-Definition-300x72.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Net-Profit-Margin-Definition-768x184.jpg 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Net-Profit-Margin-Definition.jpg 936w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p><p style="background: white;"><span style="font-family: 'Avenir',sans-serif; color: black;">These equations give management teams and potential investors different ways of slicing through the operation’s performance to help discover where costs may be excessive relative to performance.</span></p><p style="background: white;"><span style="font-family: 'Avenir',sans-serif; color: black;">The average restaurant profitability measured is 7% measured by the Net Profit Margin (based on U.S. publicly traded foodservice companies). </span></p>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-83ca9c8 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="83ca9c8" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<h2><strong>What Affects a Restaurant Profit Margin?</strong></h2><p>Some of the factors affecting the profitability level of a restaurant are the geography, the type of ownership (if it’s a franchisor, or if most of the locations are corporately owned, or if it’s a franchisee), the size (is it a big chain with hundreds of units or is it a small one with a couple dozens or an independent restaurant with one or two stores?), and the category (is it a quick-service restaurant chain or fast casual or casual dining?).</p><ul><li>Restaurant profit margins (measured by EBITDA as a percentage of sales) tend to stabilize around 12% independently of the geography — with a few exceptions.</li><li>Restaurant profitability is higher for franchised systems. Foodservice companies with highly franchised systems almost triple the profitability of those with lightly franchised systems (or not franchising at all).</li><li>Highly franchised QSR systems tend to be the most profitable, followed by highly franchised fast casual, and highly franchised casual dining.</li></ul><h2><strong>The Average Restaurant Profit Margin is Higher in Some Emerging Markets</strong></h2><p>The median restaurant profit margin is 12% in the U.S., 13% in Europe including the UK (measured by the EBITDA margins of public foodservice companies). In some markets it can be significantly lower, like Japan, with an EBITDA margin of only 3%. In emerging markets like India, the median is not very different from mature markets (close to 12%). In emerging markets like the KSA, Mexico and the Philippines, the median restaurant EBITDA margin reaches 17%.</p><p><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-21985 size-large" src="https://aaronallen.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Global-Restaurant-Margins-1024x678.jpg" alt="Box plot for EBITDA margin for six regions" width="640" height="424" srcset="https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Global-Restaurant-Margins-1024x678.jpg 1024w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Global-Restaurant-Margins-300x199.jpg 300w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Global-Restaurant-Margins-768x509.jpg 768w, https://11qkih2fw9d2h2oz31jff0fi-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Global-Restaurant-Margins.jpg 1214w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></p>					</div>
						</div>
